What is a lambda expression?
A lambda expression is a shorthand way to write an anonymous method — a method without a name — using the => syntax, called the 'goes to' operator. It makes the code more concise and readable,
especially when I'm passing a small piece of logic as a parameter, like in LINQ queries or delegates.

List<int> numbers = new List<int> { 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 };
var evenNumbers = numbers.Where(n => n % 2 == 0).ToList();


Explain LINQ.?
"LINQ stands for Language Integrated Query. It's a feature in C# that lets me query data — from collections, databases, XML, or any data source — using a consistent, 
SQL-like syntax directly in C#, instead of writing separate query logic for each data source.
List<int> numbers = new List<int> { 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6 };

var evenNumbers = numbers.Where(n => n % 2 == 0)
                          .OrderByDescending(n => n)
                          .ToList();

// Output: 6, 4, 2

IEnumerable executes the query in memory — on the client side. So if I'm querying a database using IEnumerable, it first pulls all the data into memory, and then applies the filtering, sorting, etc.
This is suited for querying in-memory collections like List or Array.

IQueryable executes the query on the data source itself — like the database. It builds an expression tree and translates it into SQL, so filtering, sorting, and paging all happen at the database level, 
and only the final result is brought into memory. This is more efficient for querying large datasets from a database using Entity Framework.

IEnumerable<Employee> emp1 = dbContext.Employees.ToList();
var result1 = emp1.Where(e => e.Salary > 50000);

// IQueryable - filtering happens in the database itself
IQueryable<Employee> emp2 = dbContext.Employees;
var result2 = emp2.Where(e => e.Salary > 50000);


What are Extension Methods?
Extension methods let me add new methods to an existing type — including built-in types or types I don't own the source code for — without modifying the original type or creating a new derived type.
They're defined as static methods in a static class, and the first parameter uses the this keyword to specify which type is being extended.
public static class StringExtensions
{
    public static bool IsValidEmail(this string str)
    {
        return str.Contains("@") && str.Contains(".");
    }
}

// Usage - looks like it's a built-in method on string
string email = "test@gmail.com";
bool result = email.IsValidEmail();   // true


What are Generics?
Generics let me write a class, method, or interface that works with any data type, without specifying the exact type in advance. Instead, the type is provided when I actually use it — this gives type 
safety at compile time and avoids boxing/unboxing, while also letting me reuse the same code for different data types.
class Box<T>
{
    public T Value;
}

Box<int> intBox = new Box<int>();
intBox.Value = 10;

Box<string> strBox = new Box<string>();
strBox.Value = "Hello";

What is async await in .net?
async and await are keywords in C# used to write asynchronous code. They allow long-running operations — like database calls or API calls — to run without blocking the main thread. 
So while that operation is in progress, the main thread is free to do other work, keeping the application responsive. Once the operation completes, execution resumes from where it left off,
usually on a thread pool thread.









